06495nam a22009015i 9781487541392DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875413927 a10.3138/97814875413922doi  a(DE-B1597)645212  a(OCoLC)1240506330  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHV640.4.C3 7aSOC0660002bisacsh04a305.9/0691422300aRefugee States :bCritical Refugee Studies in Canada /ced. by Vinh Nguyen, Thy Phu. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2021  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCultural Spaces00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Critical Refugee Studies in Canada -- tPart One: Historicization -- t1. Shifting Grounds of Asylum in Canadian Public Discourse and Policy -- t2. Untangling the Strands of Memory: Historicizing the 1914 Komagata Maru Incident and the Concept of Refugeeness -- t3. Erasing Exclusion: Adrienne Clarkson and the Promise of the Refugee Experience -- t4. Petitions and Protest: Refugees and the Haunting of Canadian Citizenship -- tPart Two: Conjunctions -- t5. Where Are We From? Decolonizing Indigenous and Refugee Relations -- t6. Queer and Trans Migrants, Colonial Logics, and the Politics of Refusal -- t7. Producing the Figure of the "Super-Refugee" through Discourses of Success, Exceptionalism, Ableism, and Inspiration -- t8. Cross-Racial Refugee Fiction: Dionne Brand's What We All Long For -- tEpilogue: The Exceptional and the Ordinary -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aExploring "refuge" and "refugee" as concepts that shape Canadian nation-building both within and beyond national borders, Refugee States takes an interdisciplinary and critical approach to describing how refugees articulate their relation to and defiance of official discourses. Through close examinations of refugee movements, contexts, and subjectivities, this collection reveals how Canada has relied upon the rejection and inclusion of refugees as a crucial means of statecraft. Bringing together renowned and emerging scholars from multiple disciplines, Nguyen and Phu illuminate the historical, political, and cultural conditions that produce refugees as well as the narrative of humanitarian benevolence that persists nationally and internationally. Highlighting landmark cases, the editors and contributors together develop critical refugee studies as a framework for understanding, nuancing, and critiquing the production of Canadian humanitarian exceptionalism - the international image and discourse of Canada as a liberal, tolerant, and welcoming haven for people fleeing oppression, persecution, and unfreedom. In doing so, Refugee States offers alternative modes of understanding past and present refugee passages to and within Canada, and brings to light the many ways in which refugee subjects navigate displacement, migration, and resettlement.  afunded by University of Toronto Libraries  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRefugeeszCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Refugees.2bisacsh  aCanadian immigration.  aDionne Brand.  aKomagata Maru.  acitizenship.  acritical refugee studies.  acultural studies.  adisplaced peoples.  adisplacement.  amigrants.  amigration.  arace.  arefuge.  arefugees.  asettler colonialism.1 aAdese, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoellnicht, Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHyndman, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul